  "text": "The Prometheus TSDB head block enforces sample time bounds through a minValidTime threshold that is set during head truncation. When Truncate() in head.go (line 1139) is called, it updates minValidTime to the specified timestamp, effectively invalidating all older samples.\n\nOut-of-bounds sample handling occurs in the append path: The Append() function in head_append.go (line 425) performs a fast-path check that immediately rejects samples with timestamps below minValidTime when out-of-order support is disabled. This increments the outOfBoundSamples counter defined in head.go's headMetrics structure (lines 478-480).\n\nFor more detailed validation, the memSeries.appendable() function (line 643 in head_append.go) checks if a sample can be appended by comparing its timestamp against: (1) minValidTime - samples below this are considered out-of-bounds, (2) the series' current max timestamp - samples must maintain order, and (3) the outOfOrderTimeWindow - if configured, allows some historical samples within a time window.\n\nThe memSeries.appendableHistogram() (line 683) and appendableFloatHistogram() (line 731) functions apply the same logic for histogram samples. When any of these validation functions identify an out-of-bounds condition, they return storage.ErrOutOfBounds.\n\nDuring commit, the handleAppendableError() function (line 1275) categorizes rejected samples. Out-of-bounds rejections are tracked separately from out-of-order rejections, with counters maintained in the appenderCommitContext. The commitFloats() function (line 1310) and its histogram variants process these rejections and update metrics.\n\nOut-of-order sample handling is managed through the OOOChunk structure in ooo_head.go, which maintains samples in time-ascending order even when they arrive out of sequence. The Insert() function (line 37 in ooo_head.go) preserves time ordering within the OOO chunk.\n\nThe head.go file defines the Head structure with the minValidTime atomic field (line 74) that governs the boundary between valid and out-of-bounds samples. The appendableMinValidTime() function (referenced in head_append.go line 175) returns the minimum timestamp accepted by the current appender, incorporating both the head's minValidTime and any out-of-order time window configuration."
}

